## Concept

A daily maintenance oil for **healed** tattoos on sun-, salt- and wind-exposed skin. Naturally derived, zero fragrance, rubbed over inked arms, legs and torso to keep the skin conditioned and the ink reading sharp. Not an aftercare product for fresh tattoos — a long-haul maintenance product for the decades after.

The honest mechanism is simple and defensible: ink sits under the skin, and what dulls it day-to-day is the condition of the skin above it. Dry, flaky, sun-beaten skin scatters light and greys the work; conditioned skin shows it. (What fades ink over years is UV — which is a sunscreen job, and the two ideas cross-reference.)

## Why it fits

The audience overlap is strong and visible: tradies, surfers, veterans and outdoor workers are among the most heavily tattooed demographics in the country, and their ink takes more environmental punishment than anyone's. The equipment-maintenance frame maps perfectly — a sleeve is *equipment you paid for*, often thousands of dollars of it, and "protect the investment" is a pitch this customer already understands from tools, boards and bikes. Zero fragrance is a genuine functional asset on large areas of skin. The voice transfers without strain.

One honest qualifier: unlike the balm (every customer has elbows), this serves a **slice** of the existing audience — a large slice, but a slice. It deepens the relationship with tattooed customers rather than all customers.

## Nature of the opportunity

The tattoo-care shelf is crowded **at the healing window** — aftercare balms for fresh ink (Bepanthen by default, Dr Pickles as the Australian success story, Hustle Butter, After Inked and many others) — and thin **in the decades after**. Almost nothing speaks to *ongoing* maintenance of healed ink on weathered, outdoor skin; the category behaves as if a tattoo stops needing care once it stops peeling. That long-maintenance gap, for this audience, in this voice, is the opportunity.

It is also the cheapest idea on file to test, for a specific reason: the product is close enough to Field Oil that **demand can be tested with positioning before anything is formulated** — content aimed at tattooed Field Team members and followers ("what the sun does to ink; what conditioned skin does for it") costs nothing and reads intent directly.

## What transfers, what changes

Transfers almost everything: the AICIS cosmetic lane; the cold-blend, anhydrous manufacturing method and the entire Production/QC module; most or all of the supplier palette (hemp, sunflower, jojoba, meadowfoam, the Vitamin E + rosemary antioxidant system); the claims discipline; the storefront and CRM.

Changes: surface area and therefore format. A face takes 3–4 drops; a sleeve, a back piece or two full legs take millilitres. The fill likely moves to **100ml**, the actives ladder likely simplifies (the premium rosehip dose that justifies a face-oil price is wasted spread across a forearm — a high-linoleic, hemp-forward carrier base does the conditioning work at a fraction of the input cost), and the price-per-ml logic drops accordingly. Same brand, same method, cheaper blend, bigger bottle.

The most interesting structural question: whether this is a distinct formula at all, or **Field Oil's little brother** — the same philosophy with a leaner recipe. It must not simply be Field Oil relabelled at a lower per-ml price, because that would invite the customer to arbitrage the face oil.

## Formulation direction

A hemp-forward, high-linoleic carrier base (hemp, sunflower) with meadowfoam for stability and feel, the existing antioxidant system carried over, and no fragrance or essential oils — which matters doubly here because tattooed skin is often sensitised skin. Fast absorption matters more than richness (nobody oils a forearm they can't then put a shirt on). The oxidation logic and argon discipline from Field Oil carry over unchanged.

No new safety questions of the pets kind — this is human topical cosmetic, the known lane.

## Format and unit economics

Likely **100ml** in the amber-glass language of the range (pump rather than dropper — dropper dosing is wrong for large areas). Cheaper base + larger fill + simpler actives means the cost per bottle can stay sane despite the volume, and the customer's mental price anchor is "quality body product", not face-oil-per-ml. Usage is genuinely consumptive (large areas, regular use), so repeat purchase is structurally better than Field Oil's three-month cadence.

*(All figures illustrative and unmodelled. Same first-principles build required as the others: base cost per ml at 100ml fill, uses per bottle, pump/bottle costs, target contribution margin.)*

## Pricing logic

Priced as a quality natural body oil with a story — meaningfully below Field Oil per ml, respectable in absolute terms. The investment-protection framing supports a premium over generic body oils: the reference point is not "moisturiser" but "the $2,000 sleeve it maintains". A Field Oil + Tattoo Oil pairing also gives the tattooed customer a natural two-product kit without discounting either.

## Regulatory pathway

Cosmetic (AICIS), same as Field Oil — **provided the positioning stays on healed skin and maintenance claims.** The line to respect: a fresh tattoo is broken skin, and products marketed for **healing fresh tattoos** drift toward therapeutic claims (wound healing) and a different regime. The clean, deliberate choice — which is also the differentiated one — is to stay out of the aftercare window entirely: "for healed ink" on the label, conditioning and appearance claims only ("keeps skin conditioned; conditioned skin shows your ink"), never "heals", "repairs" or "prevents fading" (fading is UV; don't claim it, cross-sell sun sense instead). The existing maintenance-not-treatment discipline handles this naturally. Confirm the aftercare/healed-skin claim boundary before writing final copy.

## Key risks

Focus and timing first, as with everything on file. Then: the audience-slice question (what fraction of the customer base is tattooed enough to care); the cannibalisation/arbitrage edge if the formula lands too close to Field Oil at a lower per-ml price; and channel temptation — tattoo studios are the obvious distribution channel but they mostly want healing-window products, which is exactly the positioning this deliberately avoids. Competitive risk is modest in the maintenance niche but the aftercare giants could extend into it trivially if it proves out.

## Open questions

1. What share of the current audience/Field Team is meaningfully tattooed? (Cheap to answer — ask the Field Team in the day-21 survey or a follow-up.)
2. Distinct lean formula vs Field Oil derivative: where exactly does it differ, and is the difference honest enough to defend two prices?
3. Fill and dispenser: 100ml pump assumption right? Uses per bottle at realistic coverage?
4. Does the content-first demand test (posts aimed at tattooed followers, zero product) show real pull before anything is formulated?
5. Confirmed claim boundary for healed-skin maintenance vs aftercare in Australia.
6. Standalone, kit-with-Field-Oil, or both?

## Recommendation and next trigger

Park until Field Oil is launched and the Father's Day campaign is run — but note two things in sequencing. First, it ranks **behind Barrier Balm** (which serves every customer, not a slice) and **ahead of pets and sunscreen** on cost, speed and risk. Second, it is the only idea on file with a **free pre-test**: tattoo-angle content and one survey question to the Field Team can measure demand this quarter without building anything. Run the free test whenever convenient; re-open the product itself only if the test pulls and Field Oil is stable.

